The NC State site of the Center for Accelerated Real Time Analytics (CARTA/NC State) is one partner in a multi-university industry collaborative research center dedicated to pre- competitive research in advanced data analytics with the vision of driving innovation in "Faster than Life Analytics." CARTA/NC State fostered collaborative relationships between researchers at NC State and member organizations from industry and government focused on delivering cutting-edge tools, approaches, and expertise that will significantly lower the barriers of entry into advanced, real-time analytics. These members funded eleven projects representing the diversity of interests of the Center's members, including cybersecurity, hurricane prediction, edge computing and Internet of Things, privacy-preserving analytics, and cloud computing.


These projects developed and tested new and novel techniques and algorithms that offer value-added impacts, including:




Advancements in techniques for real-time cybersecurity and cyber threat assessment/prediction information supports improved decision-making in critical information technology and security domains;




Novel analytics and machine learning algorithms merging historical and real-time atmospheric and oceanic data improve hurricane prediction, providing the opportunity to make more informed and reliable decisions on tropical storm preparedness;




New advancements in novel advanced, real-time analysis of remote sensing data, inducing image data from drones and satellites, support improved farming efficiency and production, lowering environmental impacts and delivering higher crop yields;




Insights on more efficient use of computational resources across all application domains support energy savings and reduced waste generation from computational infrastructure.




Research results and related outcomes of this work has been disseminated via 22 peer-reviewed publications, multiple Master's and PhD theses/dissertations, invited keynote presentations at international conferences, open source code and dataset repositories, and public news items. More importantly, the undergraduate and graduate students who have contributed to these research efforts have become the experts in the new knowledge and techniques. These individuals will help to spread and advance this knowledge through their future professional and academic careers.





